<p><b>Kalachakra</b> (<a href="Sanskrit" title="Sanskrit">Sanskrit</a>: <span class="Unicode">कालचक्र, <a href="IAST" title="IAST" class="mw-redirect">IAST</a>: <i>Kālacakra</i></span>; <a href="Telugu_language" title="Telugu language">Telugu</a>: కాలచక్ర <a href="Tibetan_alphabet" title="Tibetan alphabet">Tibetan</a>: <span lang="bo" style="font-family:'DDC Uchen', Kailash, Jomolhari,'Tibetan Machine Uni'; font-weight:normal; font-size:130%;" xml:lang="bo">དུས་ཀྱི་འཁོར་ལོ།</span>,&#160;<a href="Wylie_transliteration" title="Wylie transliteration">Wylie</a>: <i>dus-kyi 'khor-lo</i>; <a href="Mongolian_language" title="Mongolian language">Mongolian</a>: Цогт Цагийн Хүрдэн <i>Tsogt Tsagiin Hurden</i>; <a href="Chinese_language" title="Chinese language">Chinese</a>: 時輪) is a Sanskrit term used in <a href="Vajrayana" title="Vajrayana">Tantric Buddhism</a> that literally means "<a href="Wheel_of_time" title="Wheel of time">time-wheel</a>" or "time-cycles". The spelling <i><b>Kalacakra</b></i> is also used.</p>
<p>The word Kalachakra is usually used to refer to a very complex teaching and practice in <a href="Tibetan_Buddhism" title="Tibetan Buddhism">Tibetan Buddhism</a>. Although the teaching is very advanced, <a class="external text" href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/esoteric">esoteric</a>, and difficult to comprehend, there is a tradition of offering it to large public audiences.</p>
